    title = "{Local Structure for the Discretization of the Scalar Field Equations on Sprinkled Causal Sets}",
    abstract = "One framework for quantum gravity is causal set theory, where the classical spacetime continuum is replaced by locally finite, partially ordered sets of events (causal sets). For the description of classical (and quantum) scalar fields on causal sets, it is necessary to find a discretization of the Klein-Gordon equation.<br>In this talk, I will review a newly proposed method for discretization that does not require the dimension of the spacetime continuum as an input, but rather relies on an additional local structure derived from the rank 2 past of causal set events, which is the set of events that are two links to the past. I will show results from our most recent publication, where we investigated this local structure - called preferred past - using numerical techniques, generating ensembles of causal sets from Minkowski spacetimes by the Poisson process of sprinkling. Our results give a method that performs particularly well at uniquely selecting - with very high probability - a preferred past satisfying desirable properties.<br>This talk is based on a publication in joint work with C. J. Fewster, E. Hawkins, and K. Rejzner.",
